Thus was born CALEA: Congress mandated that communications providers =E2=80=
=94 who remember, are providing the keys for transport layer encryption =E2=
=80=94 create the capability for law enforcement to listen in on conversati=
ons, i.e. leverage their control of encryption keys to give access to the u=
nderlying data. This is the capability that was leveraged in these attacks,=
 so it=E2=80=99s not wrong to say that =E2=80=9CCongress Hacked U.S. Commun=
ications=E2=80=9D, by creating this capability in the first place=E2=80=A6

In 2004, the DOJ, ATF, FBI, and DEA filed a petition with the FCC to expand=
 CALEA to cover all IP traffic, including broadband Internet communications=
; the FCC did so, and when challenged in court, won thanks to the Chevron d=
eference doctrine, which granted substantial law-making ability to agencies=
 in lieu of explicit Congressional directions. In this case specifically th=
e court held that Congress=E2=80=99s explicit exclusion of =E2=80=9Cinforma=
tion services=E2=80=9D did not necessarily apply to broadband, which frankl=
y, still confuses me; indeed, this case is one of the stronger arguments ag=
ainst Chevron, which was overturned earlier this year.

Regardless, the pertinent takeaway for this Article is that you can argue t=
hat the =E2=80=9CFCC Hacked U.S. Communications=E2=80=9D, and the reason is=
 this: yes, the Chinese hacked into U.S. communications, but they did so vi=
a a backdoor mandated by CALEA, which was expanded to include internet comm=
unications by the FCC. Without CALEA and without that 2004 expansion there =
would not have been a vulnerability for the Chinese to hack.

The U.K. government is effectively demanding that Apple install the same so=
rt of vulnerability that led to the Salt Typhoon hack into all of its encry=
ption, and that that vulnerability be applied to everyone in the world. Oh,=
 and Apple is forbidden to say it is happening, and has to implement the ba=
ck door before its appeal is even heard. In other words, Apple has to make =
its encryption fundamentally vulnerable for all of its customers worldwide =
just because the U.K. said so.

The extent to which the U.K. government is living in a fantasy world is hon=
estly hard to fathom. First, McCallum's quote in the Financial Times is non=
sense: there's isn't a middle ground on this issue, because encryption is m=
ath; there is either a vulnerability built in or there isn't. Second, the s=
heer presumptiveness of the U.K. thinking that it has the authority to forc=
e Apple to compromise its worldwide userbase is breathtaking. It's 2025, no=
t 1925, something that no one in the U.K. seems to be aware of. Third, the =
U.K. seems completely unaware of how this is going to play out if they pres=
s this issue.

This is how I think it will go. First, I strongly suspect that these storie=
s were a leak from Apple in order to engender pressure on the U.K. to back =
down. I suggest they do so. Second, if they don't, then Apple will withdraw=
 encrypted storage from the U.K., and hopefully they say why; this could in=
clude withdrawing iMessage as well (although that won't be that big of a de=
al). This won't, of course, satisfy the U.K.'s worldwide demands; if the U.=
K. presses forward then I would expect Apple to exit the country.

The key thing to understand about the U.K.'s demands is that this is a much=
 graver issue than even the E.U.'s insistence on opening the App Store, or =
whatever other frustrations have previously led to idle speculation about A=
