Elon Musk's OpenAI Bid
----------------------

From the Wall Street Journal ( https://www.wsj.com/tech/elon-musk-openai-bi=
d-4af12827 ) :

A consortium of investors led by Elon Musk is offering $97.4 billion to buy=
 the nonprofit that controls OpenAI, raising the stakes in his battle with =
Sam Altman over the company behind ChatGPT. Musk=E2=80=99s lawyer, Marc Tob=
eroff, said he submitted a bid for all the nonprofit=E2=80=99s assets to Op=
enAI=E2=80=99s board of directors Monday. The unsolicited offer adds a comp=
lication to Altman=E2=80=99s carefully laid plans for OpenAI=E2=80=99s futu=
re, including converting it to a for-profit company and spending up to $500=
 billion on AI infrastructure through a joint venture called Stargate. He a=
nd Musk are already fighting in court over the direction of OpenAI. =E2=80=
=9CIt=E2=80=99s time for OpenAI to return to the open-source, safety-focuse=
d force for good it once was,=E2=80=9D Musk said in a statement provided by=
 Toberoff. =E2=80=9CWe will make sure that happens.=E2=80=9D

Altman quickly rejected the offer on X. He wrote, =E2=80=9CNo thank you but=
 we will buy twitter for $9.74 billion if you want,=E2=80=9D using the prev=
ious name for the Musk-owned social-media platform and moving the decimal p=
oint in the billionaire=E2=80=99s bid for OpenAI one space to the left. In =
a Slack message to employees, Altman wrote, =E2=80=9COur structure ensures =
that no individual can take control of OpenAI=E2=80=A6These are tactics to =
try and weaken us because we are making great progress.=E2=80=9D

Altman is right, of course, which is exactly his problem. Namely, the OpenA=
I non-profit is controlled by its board, which does not have a fiduciary du=
ty to maximize OpenAI's value. That means it can say no! At the same time, =
the structure that lets OpenAI's board say "No" is exactly what Altman is t=
rying to get rid of, in favor of a for-profit structure that will unlock ne=
w investment (and which is reportedly a condition of the company's most rec=
ent fundraising rounds).

It is not, for the record, illegal, impossible, or even unprecedented for a=
 non-profit to convert to a for-profit entity; to do so at the scale of Ope=
nAI =E2=80=94 which may be on the verge of raising $40 billion at a $300 bi=
llion valuation ( https://www.nytimes.com/2025/02/07/technology/openai-soft=
bank-investment.html ) =E2=80=94 is what is novel. The most important requi=
rement is that the non-profit sell its assets at fair market value; the big=
 question is what that value is. Indeed, I've already clouded the picture, =
because that potential $300 billion valuation is not for the non-profit, bu=
t rather the for-profit entity that licenses OpenAI's assets from the non-p=
rofit entity and which has promised profit shares to its investors, most no=
tably Microsoft. The question, then, is how to balance the worth of those p=
rofit share promises versus the underlying assets.

Altman and the OpenAI investors are heavily incentivized to give more weigh=
t to those potential profits, which would decrease the share of the for-pro=
fit company that the non-profit is entitled to. M.G. Siegler has speculated=
 on Spyglass ( https://spyglass.org/the-war-of-the-ai-roses/ ) that the non=
-profit would get 25% of the for-profit entity, which at a $300 billion val=
uation would be $75 billion; I personally think that the assets are worth m=
ore than that, in part because I think the "ChatGPT" brand is particularly =
valuable in becoming a consumer tech company ( https://stratechery.com/2023=
/the-accidental-consumer-tech-company-chatgpt-meta-and-product-market-fit-a=
ggregation-and-apis/?access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWN=
